.pl 62















                     DEFINICON SYSTEMS, INC.

                    DSI-32 COPROCESSOR BOARD
                   & MS/PC DOS SYSTEM SOFTWARE














          INTERFACING HIGH LEVEL LANGUAGES
          AND ASSEMBLER LANGUAGE
.pa
1.0 Interfacing C, Pascal and Fortran to assembler

     Some  applications require both high level language code  as 
well as assembler code. For these applications it is necessary to 
be  able to link the two language types together to form a single 
program. This document describes how interface language types and 
how parameters are passed between them.

     For   further  reference  on  the  assembler  syntax  and  a 
discussion on assembler procedures and parameter passing refer to 
the Defincon Assembler/Linker document.

     One of the advantages of the Definicon C, Pascal and Fortran 
compilers  is the common code generator that they all share.  The 
common code generator means that the same interfacing  techniques 
will apply to all three languages. Below is an outline of how the 
three languages pass their parameters on the stack.

  o   C.

      The  C  language  can pass parameters by  either  value  or 
      pointer.  Which  type  of parameter gets passed  is  purely 
      dependent the C program.

  o   Pascal.

      The  Pascal language can pass parameters by either value or       
      pointer.  Which  type  of parameter gets passed  is  purely       
      dependent the Pascal program.

  o   Fortran.

      The  Fortran language passes parameters by pointer,  ie the 
      item  that  gets passed on the stack is a  pointer  to  the       
      actual parameter.

In the following sections there are three examples,  one for each 
language.  The  astute  person will note that the  C  and  Pascal 
languages  produce identical assembler output for the  equivalent 
test  program.  Fortran  on  the  other  hand  produces  entirely 
different  code,  primarily because the parameters are passed  by 
pointer (ie by reference). In each of the three examples there is 
also  an example program written in assembler to interface to the 
high level language program.
.pa
1.1 C calling convention

Below  is  an  example C program which calls  a  function  called 
'asm1'  and  passes  two pointers and a value.  Variable  'a'  is 
passed  to  the  'asm1' function by reference  as  is  the  first 
element of the 'c' array, while variable 'b' is passed by value.

test()
{
     int  a, b;
     char c[10];

     asm1(&a, b, &c[0]);
}

The actual assembler code that is produced for this C program  is 
shown below:

 .module	test.c
 .program
 _main:-
	enter	[],16              ;16 bytes = a + b + c[10]
	addrd	-14(fp),tos        ;address of c
	movd	r0,tos             ;value of b
	addrd	-4(fp),tos         ;address of a
	cxp	_asm1              ;call the function
	adjspb	-12                ;collapse stack back
	exit	[]                 ;exit from stack frame
	rxp	0                  ;done
 .endseg
 ;_a	-4(fp)	local
 ;_b	r0	local
 ;_c	-14(fp)	local
	.importp	_asm1
.pa
1.2 Pascal calling convention

Below is an example Pascal program which calls a function  called 
'asm1'  and  passes  two pointers and a value.  Variable  'a'  is 
passed  to  the  'asm1' function by reference  as  is  the  first 
element of the 'c' array, while variable 'b' is passed by value.

    type
	string = array[0..9] of char;
    procedure asm1(var a:integer; b:integer; var c:string); external;

procedure test;
    var
	a, b: integer;
	c: string;
begin
    asm1(a, b ,c);
end;

The  actual  assembler  code  that is produced  for  this  Pascal 
program is shown below:

 .module	test1.p
 .program
 _test:-
	enter	[],16              ;16 bytes = a + b + c[10]
	addrd	-14(fp),tos        ;address of c
	movd	r0,tos             ;value of b
	addrd	-4(fp),tos         ;address of a
	cxp	_asm1              ;call the function
	adjspb	-12                ;collapse stack back
	exit	[]                 ;exit from stack frame
	rxp	0                  ;done
 .endseg
 ;_a	-4(fp)	local
 ;_b	r0	local
 ;_c	-14(fp)	local
	.importp	_asm1

.pa
1.3 Assembler program example for C or Pascal

Below  is  an  example  of  how to write  the  asm1  function  in 
assembler.  Since  the  compiler  output from the  C  and  Pascal 
compilers  is  the  same,  this one assembler code  program  will 
suffice for both.

          exportp   _asm1

_asm1:    proc
c:        blkd      1              ;order of variables on stack
b:        blkd      1              ; is the order  they  were 
a:        blkd      1              ; push in
          returns
          blkd      3              ;must fake return of a, b & c
          var       []
          begin
          addd      b,0(a)         ;add 'b' to contents of 'a'
          movd      'done',0(c)    ;put 'done...' with zero
          movd      '...',4(c)     ; terminator
          endproc

The  listing  file  for the above assembler language  program  is 
shown below:
.cw 10

				     1            exportp   _asm1
				     2  
				     3  _asm1:    proc
				     4  c:        blkd      1
				     5  b:        blkd      1 
				     6  a:        blkd      1
				     7            returns
				     8            blkd      3
				     9            var       []
00000000 PC 820000		    10            begin
00000003 PC 03c4100c00		    11            addd      b,0(a)
00000008 PC 17a4656e6f641400	    12            movd      'done',0(c)
00000010 PC 17a4002e2e2e1404	    13            movd      '...',4(c)
00000018 PC 92003200		    14            endproc


NAME                         EXT  REL   VALUE   VALUE  DEFINED REFERENCES

a                                 FP  0000000c              6     11
b                                 FP  00000010              5     11
c                                 FP  00000014              4     12  13
_asm1                        EXP  PC  00000000              3      1
.cw 12
.pa
Some points to note about the above assembler program follow:

1)   After the 'proc' pseudo-op are the definitions for reserving 
     the  space for the variables passed by the calling  routine. 
     Sufficient  memory  has  to be reserved for all  the  passed 
     variables.

2)   After  the 'returns' pseudo-op  is the  definition  for  the 
     amount of data passed back to the calling function. Since in 
     both C and Pascal it is the calling routines task to unstack 
     the  passed  parameters the procedure must return  the  same 
     amount of data that was passed to it.

3)   The 'var' pseudo-op can if necessary inform the assembler to 
     save  some of the general purpose registers (R0  - R7).  Any 
     general  purpose registers that need to be saved are  placed 
     between  the  square  brackets,   separated  by  commas,  eg 
     [R3,  R4].  Note  that  in both the C and  Pascal  compilers 
     registers  R0,  R1 and R2 may be changed by a function,  but 
     registers R3,  R4,  R5,  R6 and R7 must be  preserved.  Also 
     floating point registers F0,  F1,  F2 and F3 may be changed, 
     but registers F4, F5, F6 and F7 must be preserved.

4)   If  a  procedure has to return a result  to a  C  or  Pascal       
     function  then  that  result  must be  returned  in  the  R0 
     register for integer results  or in the F0,F1 floating point      
     register pair if it is a floating point result.

5)   Since all variables to the procedure are passed on the frame 
     the  procedure may recursively call itself if required.  The 
     level  of  recursion  is solely limited  by  the  amount  of      
     available stack.
.pa
1.4 Fortran calling convention

Below is an example Fortran program which calls a function called 
'asm1' and passes three variables, 'a', 'b' and 'c' by reference.

	program test
	integer a,b
	character*10 c

	call asm1(a,b,c)
	end

The  actual  assembler  code that is produced  for  this  Fortran 
program is shown below:

 .module	test3.f
 .program
 _MAIN_:-
	addrd	@10,tos            ;the size of array c
	addrd	L8,tos             ;pointer to array c
 	addrd	L6,tos             ;pointer to b
	addrd	L7,tos             ;pointer to a
	cxp	_asm1_
	adjspb	-16
	rxp	0
 .endseg
 L7:	.blkb	4
 L6:	.blkb	4
 L8:	.blkb	8
	.word	0
	.importp	_asm1_

Below  is  an  example  of  how to write  the  asm1  function  in 
assembler.

          exportp   _asm1
_asm1:    proc
d:        blkd      1              ;sizeof array c
c:        blkd      1              ;order of variables on stack
b:        blkd      1              ; is the order  they  were 
a:        blkd      1              ; push in
          returns
          blkd      4              ;fake return of a, b, c & d
          var       []
          begin
          addd      0(b),0(a)      ;add 'b' to contents of 'a'
          movd      'done',0(c)    ;put 'done...' with zero
          movd      '...',4(c)     ; terminator
          endproc

.pa
The  listing  file  for the above assembler language  program  is 
shown below:
.cw 10



				     1            exportp   _asm1
				     2  
				     3  _asm1:    proc
                                     4  d:        blkd      1
				     5  c:        blkd      1
				     6  b:        blkd      1
				     7  a:        blkd      1
				     8            returns
				     9            blkd      3 
				    10            var       []
00000000 PC 820000		    11            begin
00000003 PC 038410000c00            12            addd      0(b),0(a)
00000009 PC 17a4656e6f641400	    13            movd      'done',0(c)
00000010 PC 17a4002e2e2e1404	    14            movd      '...',4(c)
00000018 PC 92003200		    15            endproc

NAME                         EXT  REL   VALUE  VALUE  DEFINED  REFERENCES

a                                 FP  0000000c            7   12
b                                 FP  00000010            6   12
c                                 FP  00000014            5   13 14
d                                 FP  00000018            4
_asm1                        EXP  PC  00000000            3    1



.cw 12
Notes  1)  2) and 3) from the C / Pascal assembler  example  also 
apply  to this Fortran example.  Note that in the Fortran example 
the size of the array is also passed to the assembler  procedure. 
Unless the size is actually required within the procedure then it 
may just be ignored.
.pa
1.5 Building the executable program

Now  that  we  have  written both the  high  level  language  and 
assembler  language portions of the code it is time to build  the 
executable  program.  Firstly  it  is necessary  to  compile  and 
assemble the high level language portion.

For C programs:

     A>cc test
     A>as test
 
or for Pascal programs:

     A>pc test1
     A>as test1

or for Fortran programs:

     A>fc test2
     A>as test2

Now  we  have to assemble the assembler language portion  of  the 
code:

     A>as asm1

All  that  is  now necessary is to link the high  level  language 
portion to the assembler language portion:

For the C example:

     A>ln file=test,asm1

or for the Pascal example:

     A>ln file=test1,asm1

or for the Fortran example:

     A>ln file=test2,asm1

And to execute the resultant program all that is necessary is  to 
use  the  standard  Definicon  loader  program,  see  section  on 
invoking the 'LOAD' program.
.pa
2.0 High level language to high level language

In  some cases it is necessary to interface high  level  language 
programs together.  The Definicon C, Pascal and Fortran compilers 
share a common code generator.  This means that parameter passing 
to functions,  procedures or subroutines is performed in the same 
manner regardless of the language.  As seen in the last section C 
and  Pascal  are  very compatible while Fortran  may  pass  extra 
parameters  if required.  Nevertheless,  separately compiled  and 
assembled  modules  may  be  linked together  to  form  a  single 
program.  In fact all the libraries for the compilers; CLIB, PLIB 
and FLIB are all written in the C language.

The  major difference between the languages is that C and  Pascal 
normally   pass  variables  by  value,   and  Fortran  passes  by 
reference.  This means that the statement  'asm1(&a,  b,  &c[0])' 
in  C  passes  the  variable 'b' by value,  and 'a'  and  'c'  by 
reference.  Specifically, the CONTENTS of 'b' are passed, and the 
ADDRESS of 'a' and 'c' are passed.

As  an  example  of how to invoke a function written  in  C  from 
within a program written in Fortran, see below:

     program fortest
     integer a,b
     character*10 c

     call cfunct(a, b, c)
     end

Now  we  will write the C function that was invoked in the  above 
Fortran program.

     cfunct(a, b, c, d)
     int *a, *b;         /* pointers to integer variables */
     char *c;            /* pointer to character array */
     int d;              /* the size of the character array */
     {
          int i = d;
          static char done[] = "done.............."

          *a = *a + *b;       /* add b to contents of a */
          ptr = done;
          while (d--)         /* for the size of the array */
               *c++ = done[i-d];
          *c = '\0';          /* append null */
     }

Note.  When  an array is passed to a subroutine in  Fortran,  the 
size  of  the  array is also implicitly  passed.  See  the  above 
example with reference to the 'd' variable in the C program.
